<subSubSection id="89A6C9CBFFFFBA3EFC9EF9B8FD7DFF44" lastPageId="31" lastPageNumber="922" pageId="30" pageNumber="921" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="C1039A40FFFFBA3EFC9EF9B8FD7DFF44" blockId="30.[835,1475,1547,2083]" lastBlockId="31.[113,752,189,246]" lastPageId="31" lastPageNumber="922" pageId="30" pageNumber="921">
<emphasis id="F3C84652FFFFBA3FFC9EF9B8FC23F992" bold="true" box="[835,942,1547,1571]" pageId="30" pageNumber="921">Remarks</emphasis>
. As discussed earlier, what used to be called 
<taxonomicName id="06BCE1C3FFFFBA3FFC99F998FBD7F9F2" baseAuthorityName="Dana" baseAuthorityYear="1851" box="[836,1114,1579,1603]" class="Malacostraca" family="Sesarmidae" genus="Chiromantes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="30" pageNumber="921" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obtusifrons">
<emphasis id="F3C84652FFFFBA3FFC99F998FBD7F9F2" box="[836,1114,1579,1603]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="921">Chiromantes obtusifrons</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is now a group of five species (
<bibRefCitation id="A52DE7B1FFFFBA3FFC96F9F8FB92F9D2" author="Davie PJF &amp; Ng PKL" box="[843,1055,1611,1635]" pageId="30" pageNumber="921" pagination="1 - 25" refId="ref68942" refString="Davie PJF &amp; Ng PKL (2013) A review of Chiromantes obtusifrons (Dana, 1851) (Decapoda: Brachyura: Sesarmidae), with descriptions of four new sibling-species from Christmas Island, Guam and Taiwan. Zootaxa, 3609 (1): 1 - 25." type="journal article" year="2013">Davie &amp; Ng, 2013</bibRefCitation>
), all sharing a peculiar frontal margin that is very broad and prominently bent downwards such that much of the antennae and antennules are completely covered in frontal view. The broad front also results in a pecular carapace shape—clearly trapezoidal with the posterolateral margins strongly converging towards the posterior carapace margin, but with the lateral margins arcuate, resulting in a transversely subovate form (
<figureCitation id="598786C5FFFFBA3FFBB4F898FB7EF8F2" box="[1129,1267,1835,1859]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="26.[136,171,1910,1932]" captionTargetBox="[136,1474,199,1895]" captionTargetId="figure-8@26.[136,1474,199,1895]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="Fig. 13. Overall habitus. A, Danarma obtusifrons, male (17.7 × 13.2 mm) (UF-FLMNH 14837), Oahu, Hawaii; B, Danarma silus, holotype male (16.3 × 12.8 mm) (ZRC 2012.0787), Guam; C, Danarma eurymerus, holotype male (18.7 × 14.8 mm) (NMNS-7028-002), Lanyu Island, Taiwan; D, Danarma garfunkel, holotype male (17.0 × 13.0 mm) (QM), Greta Beach, Christmas Island; E, Cristarma eulimene, male (22.2 × 17.2 mm) (ZRC 1968.1.22.2), Inhaca Island, Mozambique; F, Cristarma ortmanni, male (20.0 × 15.5 mm) (ZRC 1968.1.22.1), Inhaca Island, Mozambique; G, Trapezarma angolense, neotype male (39.3 × 32.7 mm) (SMF-ZMG 635), Benguella, Angola; H, Platychirarma buettikoferi, paralectotype male (10.0 × 8.7 mm) (SMF-ZMG 636), Fisherman Lake, Liberia; I, Platychirarma buettikoferi, lectotype male (14.1 × 11.6 mm) (RMNH D 148), Liberia; J, Platychirarma buettikoferi, male (12.6 × 10.4 mm) (ZRC 2015.0298), Cameroon." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5351323" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5351323/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="921">Figs. 13A–D</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="598786C5FFFFBA3FFB21F898FAC3F8F2" box="[1276,1358,1835,1859]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="28.[136,171,1850,1872]" captionTargetBox="[136,1474,287,1835]" captionTargetId="figure-7@28.[136,1474,287,1835]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="Fig. 14. Frontal view of cephalothorax. A, Danarma obtusifrons, male (17.7 × 13.2 mm) (UF-FLMNH 14837), Hawaii; B, Danarma garfunkel, holotype male (17.0 × 13.0 mm) (QM, ex ZRC 2009.0822), Christmas Island; C, D, Danarma eurymerus, holotype male (18.7 × 14.8 mm) (NMNS-7028-002), Lanyu Island, Taiwan; E, Cristarma eulimene, male (22.2 × 17.2 mm) (ZRC 1968.1.22.2), Inhaca Island, Mozambique; F, Cristarma ortmanni, male (20.0 × 15.5 mm) (ZRC 1968.1.22.1), Inhaca Island, Mozambique; G, Trapezarma angolense, neotype male (39.3 × 32.7 mm) (SMF-ZMG 635), Benguella, Angola; H, Platychirarma buettikoferi, paralectotype male (10.0 × 8.7 mm) (SMF-ZMG 636), Fisherman Lake, Liberia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5351325" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5351325/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="921">14A–D</figureCitation>
). The outer surface of the palm is also smooth, with no longitudinal ridge, the dactylar finger completely unarmed on the dorsal margin (
<figureCitation id="598786C5FFFFBA3FFC42F838FBA9F812" box="[927,1060,1931,1955]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="30.[136,171,1412,1434]" captionTargetBox="[136,1474,189,1397]" captionTargetId="figure-8@30.[136,1474,189,1397]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="Fig. 15. Chela. A, B, Danarma eurymerus, holotype male (18.7 × 14.8 mm) (NMNS-7028–002), Lanyu Island, Taiwan; C, D, Cristarma eulimene, male (22.2 × 17.2 mm) (ZRC 1968.1.22.2), Inhaca Island, Mozambique; E, F, Cristarma ortmanni, male (20.0 × 15.5 mm) (ZRC 1968.1.22.1), Inhaca Island, Mozambique. A, C, E, outer view; B, inner view; D, F, dorso-lateral view showing pectinated ridge on palm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5351327" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5351327/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="921">Fig. 15A, B</figureCitation>
), and the surfaces between the first to third ambulatory coxae have distinct dense tufts of long setae (
<figureCitation id="598786C5FFFFBA3FFC96F878FC5CF852" box="[843,977,1995,2019]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="34.[136,171,1517,1539]" captionTargetBox="[136,1474,189,1501]" captionTargetId="figure-8@34.[136,1474,189,1501]" captionTargetPageId="34" captionText="Fig. 18. Male anterior thoracic sternum and pleon. A, Danarma obtusifrons, male (19.7 × 14.7 mm) (ZRC 2002.0220), Oahu, Hawaii; B, Danarma eurymerus, holotype male (18.7 × 14.8 mm) (NMNS-7028-002), Lanyu Island, Taiwan; C, Cristarma eulimene, male (22.2 × 17.2 mm) (ZRC 1968.1.22.2), Inhaca Island, Mozambique; D, Cristarma ortmanni, male (20.0 × 15.5 mm) (ZRC 1968.1.22.1), Inhaca Island, Mozambique; E, Trapezarma angolense, neotype male (39.3 × 32.7 mm) (SMF-ZMG 635), Benguella, Angola; F, Platychirarma buettikoferi, paralectotype male (10.0 × 8.7 mm) (SMF-ZMG 636), Fisherman Lake, Liberia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5351333" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5351333/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="921">Fig. 18A, B</figureCitation>
). The presence of strongly setose ambulatory coxae is a feature shared with species of 
<taxonomicName id="06BCE1C3FFFFBA3FFACBF858FA08F7B3" authority="Schubart &amp; Ng, 2020" authorityName="Schubart &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2020" box="[1302,1413,2027,2050]" class="Malacostraca" family="Sesarmidae" genus="Cristarma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="30" pageNumber="921" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="new genus">
<emphasis id="F3C84652FFFFBA3FFACBF858FA08F7B3" box="[1302,1413,2027,2050]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="921">Cristarma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel id="E8FBFB29FFFFBA3FFA48F858FC09F792" pageId="30" pageNumber="921" rank="genus">new genus</taxonomicNameLabel>
, from East Africa (see later). This suite of distinctive characters shared by five similar species is strong support for the establishment of a new genus, here named 
<taxonomicName id="06BCE1C3FFFEBA3EFD5EFF6DFD64FF44" authorityName="Schubart &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2020" box="[643,745,222,245]" class="Malacostraca" family="Sesarmidae" genus="Danarma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="31" pageNumber="922" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="F3C84652FFFEBA3EFD5EFF6DFD64FF44" box="[643,745,222,245]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="922">Danarma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
